WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.350 --> 00:00:03.430
Prof: Good morning,
let us begin.

00:00:03.430 --> 00:00:07.334
Today we're going to move away
from the first dimension of

00:00:07.334 --> 00:00:09.800
music that we've been looking
at,

00:00:09.800 --> 00:00:12.911
which is duration,
or time, and begin to work with

00:00:12.911 --> 00:00:15.390
the second,
which is pitch, and melody.

00:00:15.390 --> 00:00:19.090
And here's an initial question
for you.

00:00:19.090 --> 00:00:22.522
Think of the texture of music
and think of these strands of

00:00:22.522 --> 00:00:23.410
high and low.
 

00:00:23.410 --> 00:00:27.700
Where does melody sit in the
texture?

00:00:27.700 --> 00:00:30.560
Is it high, middle or low?
 

00:00:30.560 --> 00:00:31.660
Where is it?
 

00:00:31.660 --> 00:00:33.170
If you think about it
conceptually,

00:00:33.170 --> 00:00:35.480
try to figure out,
well, I got this board up here,

00:00:35.480 --> 00:00:36.812
this tapestry,
or whatever,

00:00:36.812 --> 00:00:39.067
where's my melody going to be
in the texture:

00:00:39.067 --> 00:00:41.570
high,
middle or low?

00:00:41.570 --> 00:00:42.310
Michael?
 

00:00:42.310 --> 00:00:42.850
Student:  It would be
high.

00:00:42.850 --> 00:00:44.210
Prof: Yeah, usually high.
 

00:00:44.210 --> 00:00:47.068
Now, here's an interesting
question for you,

00:00:47.068 --> 00:00:48.730
why is it usually high?
 

00:00:48.730 --> 00:00:51.720
There's an acoustical reason
for this.

00:00:51.720 --> 00:00:55.520
Why does the melody show up in
the high range?

00:00:55.520 --> 00:00:56.860
Student:
&gt;

00:00:56.860 --> 00:00:57.470
Prof: I beg your pardon?
 

00:00:57.470 --> 00:00:58.700
Student:  It's easier to
hear.

00:00:58.700 --> 00:01:00.609
Prof: It's easier to
hear in a high range.

00:01:00.609 --> 00:01:03.490
Why is it easier to hear in a
high range?

00:01:03.490 --> 00:01:05.370
What about the acoustics here?
 

00:01:05.370 --> 00:01:07.159
Once again, the laws of
acoustics.

00:01:07.159 --> 00:01:10.090
Why is it easier to hear in a
high range?

00:01:10.090 --> 00:01:12.161
I could play for you,
for example,

00:01:12.161 --> 00:01:13.730
a little bit of Mozart.
 

00:01:13.730 --> 00:01:14.709
It would sound like this.
 

00:01:14.709 --> 00:01:21.430
&gt;
 

00:01:21.430 --> 00:01:24.140
You like that?
 

00:01:24.140 --> 00:01:30.709
&gt;
 

00:01:30.709 --> 00:01:32.129
Sounds better up there,
doesn't it?

00:01:32.129 --> 00:01:33.090
Why is that the case?
 

00:01:33.090 --> 00:01:33.690
Yeah.
 

00:01:33.690 --> 00:01:36.512
Student:  Maybe you can
put the frequency of the higher

00:01:36.512 --> 00:01:39.010
pitches as high so you can
detect the sound quicker and

00:01:39.010 --> 00:01:40.400
&gt;.
 

00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:41.700
Prof: That's it exactly.
 

00:01:41.700 --> 00:01:43.714
In a melody,
we tend to have a lot of

00:01:43.714 --> 00:01:45.170
rhythmic activity there.
 

00:01:45.170 --> 00:01:47.650
It's got to have activity to
play itself out as melody.

00:01:47.650 --> 00:01:55.766
But because the way sound waves
operate, we have these low sound

00:01:55.766 --> 00:02:01.049
waves taking a very long time to
clear.

00:02:01.049 --> 00:02:05.250
The higher frequencies take a
lot shorter time to clear.

00:02:05.250 --> 00:02:06.890
They're short sound waves.
 

00:02:06.890 --> 00:02:08.218
They clear very quickly.
 

00:02:08.218 --> 00:02:12.877
So, we can hear a melody--we
can hear a melody more clearly

00:02:12.877 --> 00:02:16.169
in this higher register and
therefore,

00:02:16.169 --> 00:02:19.938
there is always the tendency to
have the bass play long,

00:02:19.938 --> 00:02:24.324
low notes because those sounds
take a long time to clear and

00:02:24.324 --> 00:02:28.187
melodies play faster notes
because those sounds clear

00:02:28.187 --> 00:02:31.830
quickly and we can hear and
enjoy the melody.

00:02:31.830 --> 00:02:34.753
All right, that's just an
opening thought about why

00:02:34.753 --> 00:02:37.680
melodies show up in the top part
of the texture.

00:02:37.680 --> 00:02:40.008
Let's talk about melody here
and let's talk about pitch.

00:02:40.008 --> 00:02:46.520
We said before that in Western
music we have musical notation.

00:02:46.520 --> 00:02:50.010
And musical notation is relied
on more in Western music than

00:02:50.010 --> 00:02:52.970
any other musical civilization
around the world.

00:02:52.970 --> 00:02:55.596
And in the West,
this whole idea of pitch

00:02:55.596 --> 00:02:58.419
notation goes back to the ninth
century,

00:02:58.419 --> 00:03:02.318
when the monks and nuns in
Benedictine abbeys in

00:03:02.318 --> 00:03:06.632
Switzerland and France and
Germany and northern Italy

00:03:06.632 --> 00:03:10.425
started doing this;
they started marking on

00:03:10.425 --> 00:03:14.610
parchment or slate the general
course of a melody.

00:03:14.610 --> 00:03:20.476
Eventually, what they did was
to separate these lines into

00:03:20.476 --> 00:03:25.520
more discreet places,
or more discreet pitches.

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:27.663
Then around one thousand in
northern Italy,

00:03:27.663 --> 00:03:30.622
an enterprising fellow named
Guido of Arezzo came along and

00:03:30.622 --> 00:03:32.460
said, "Well,
you know what?

00:03:32.460 --> 00:03:39.919
I can get this to show us how
far up we are supposed to go,

00:03:39.919 --> 00:03:42.114
by placing it on some kind of
grid here,"

00:03:42.114 --> 00:03:44.262
and this is this--
as I said before,

00:03:44.262 --> 00:03:47.918
the beginning of the first
graph in the history of the

00:03:47.918 --> 00:03:48.470
West.
 

00:03:48.470 --> 00:03:52.461
This grid of horizontal lines
(and we will know that if we're

00:03:52.461 --> 00:03:55.920
going from here to here),
it's got to be exactly this

00:03:55.920 --> 00:03:58.449
frequency, or at least this
space.

00:03:58.449 --> 00:04:01.899
So, initially they came up with
four lines and then eventually

00:04:01.899 --> 00:04:04.669
five and even six,
and then they went back to five

00:04:04.669 --> 00:04:06.310
by the fifteenth century.
 

00:04:06.310 --> 00:04:11.051
What they also did around the
year one thousand was to

00:04:11.051 --> 00:04:15.794
identify--to label--these
particular spots--spaces and

00:04:15.794 --> 00:04:16.689
lines.
 

00:04:16.689 --> 00:04:21.658
So they began to call this A
and this B and this C and this D

00:04:21.658 --> 00:04:24.060
and this E, this F,
this G.

00:04:24.060 --> 00:04:28.759
When they got up here,
they stopped.

00:04:28.759 --> 00:04:31.620
Why did they stop?
 

00:04:31.620 --> 00:04:34.055
Why didn't they keep right on
going with G,

00:04:34.055 --> 00:04:35.680
H, I, J, K, L,
M, N, O, P?

00:04:35.680 --> 00:04:38.519
Why don't we sing Ms and Os and
Ps today?

00:04:38.519 --> 00:04:40.250
Why did they stop?
 

00:04:40.250 --> 00:04:41.480
Any ideas?
 

00:04:41.480 --> 00:04:42.620
&gt;
 

00:04:42.620 --> 00:04:44.180
Roger?
 

00:04:44.180 --> 00:04:46.440
Student: 
&gt;

00:04:46.440 --> 00:04:48.735
Prof: Yeah,
they had this thing--they hit

00:04:48.735 --> 00:04:50.250
this thing called the octave.
 

00:04:50.250 --> 00:04:51.810
And, of course,
there's this--another

00:04:51.810 --> 00:04:54.067
acoustical phenomenon here we've
talked about before,

00:04:54.067 --> 00:04:56.019
what's the relationship within
an octave?

00:04:56.019 --> 00:04:59.374
The string is vibrating higher
when it's exactly twice what the

00:04:59.374 --> 00:05:00.240
lower one is .
 

00:05:00.240 --> 00:05:03.742
So, they heard this and they
heard this as essentially all

00:05:03.742 --> 00:05:04.480
one sound.
 

00:05:04.480 --> 00:05:07.956
So, if it's a duplication of
sound, let's duplicate the

00:05:07.956 --> 00:05:08.600
letters.
 

00:05:08.600 --> 00:05:12.125
But you can look at manuscripts
of the early eleventh century

00:05:12.125 --> 00:05:15.711
and see people singing Ps and Ls
and Os and Ms and things like

00:05:15.711 --> 00:05:16.240
that.
 

00:05:16.240 --> 00:05:18.526
But eventually,
they began to uniformly adopt

00:05:18.526 --> 00:05:21.750
this system of what's called
"octave duplication."

00:05:21.750 --> 00:05:24.930
And every musical culture
around the world--

00:05:24.930 --> 00:05:26.826
and I've talked with
ethnomusicologists about this

00:05:26.826 --> 00:05:29.132
particular point--
every musical culture around

00:05:29.132 --> 00:05:31.339
the world,
Chinese, Japanese,

00:05:31.339 --> 00:05:34.254
Indonesian, Indian,
African whatever,

00:05:34.254 --> 00:05:38.029
they all use this phenomenon of
octave duplication in their

00:05:38.029 --> 00:05:40.829
music--
octave duplication in the music.

00:05:40.829 --> 00:05:44.742
But how they divide up this
sonic space within the octave

00:05:44.742 --> 00:05:46.910
can vary rather considerably.
 

00:05:46.910 --> 00:05:50.487
Some Arabic music seems to have
as many as fourteen gradations

00:05:50.487 --> 00:05:51.660
within the octave.
 

00:05:51.660 --> 00:05:55.730
Now, we're going to listen to a
piece of music here from the

00:05:55.730 --> 00:06:00.077
tradition of classical India and
I thought we might have a sitar

00:06:00.077 --> 00:06:01.389
player in here.
 

00:06:01.389 --> 00:06:04.399
Somebody--I got wind of the
fact we might have a classical

00:06:04.399 --> 00:06:07.396
Indian musician in our class,
somebody that had studied the

00:06:07.396 --> 00:06:09.920
sitar and might be able to come
in and play one for us.

00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:13.733
But we don't have that,
so we're going to use something

00:06:13.733 --> 00:06:17.689
on our CDs by the world famous
sitarist, Ravi Shankar.

00:06:17.689 --> 00:06:19.250
Okay, you've probably heard of
him.

00:06:19.250 --> 00:06:20.569
He's actually quite old now.
 

