He must be--surely he's in his
eighties.

00:06:21.769 --> 00:06:25.221
He was very famous when I was
in graduate school tons and tons

00:06:25.221 --> 00:06:26.069
of years ago.
 

00:06:26.069 --> 00:06:29.620
So--but he is the
venerable sitar player.

00:06:29.620 --> 00:06:33.540
And here is the pattern,
the raga.

00:06:33.540 --> 00:06:34.810
We'll call it a scale.
 

00:06:34.810 --> 00:06:37.579
It's not really a scale but a
raga that he is using.

00:06:37.579 --> 00:06:39.480
It's got only six notes within
the octave.

00:06:39.480 --> 00:06:42.329
&gt;
 

00:06:42.329 --> 00:06:53.550
Prof: And the six notes
are--&gt;

00:06:53.550 --> 00:06:55.110
--that particular pattern.
 

00:06:55.110 --> 00:06:57.759
Doesn't sound like any scale
we've ever heard of.

00:06:57.759 --> 00:07:01.973
So, let's listen to Ravi
Shankar play a bit of a raga

00:07:01.973 --> 00:07:04.000
using a six-note scale.
 

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:28.610
&gt;
 

00:07:28.610 --> 00:07:32.994
Okay, so that gives you a
flavor of that and you have

00:07:32.994 --> 00:07:36.197
that, of course,
on your CD number six,

00:07:36.197 --> 00:07:37.209
fifteen.
 

00:07:37.209 --> 00:07:41.129
So that's a bit of sitar music.
 

00:07:41.129 --> 00:07:44.149
Now, we're going to play
another six-note scale.

00:07:44.149 --> 00:07:46.860
Let's go onto that one when
Lynda gets set.

00:07:46.860 --> 00:07:50.440
And this, of course,
is sung by Nora Jones.

00:07:50.440 --> 00:07:53.088
And, as you know from reading
the textbook,

00:07:53.088 --> 00:07:54.980
why do I mention Nora Jones?
 

00:07:54.980 --> 00:07:57.980
Or why do we play Nora Jones
right after Ravi Shankar?

00:07:57.980 --> 00:07:58.857
Student:  It's his
daughter..

00:07:58.857 --> 00:07:59.709
Prof: It's his
daughter.

00:07:59.709 --> 00:08:01.740
Isn't that interesting?
 

00:08:01.740 --> 00:08:04.855
Every Saturday morning I'm
going through Stop 'N Shop and

00:08:04.855 --> 00:08:07.470
there's Nora Jones in the
